{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What the FFN Sublayer Is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Every transformer block contains two sublayers: multi-head attention followed by a position-wise feed-forward network (FFN). The FFN is applied "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "independently and identically"}, {"type": "text", "text": " to each token position — the same two linear layers with the same weights, but run separately for position 0, position 1, position 2, and so on. It does not mix information across positions; that is the job of attention. The FFN's role is to process the representation of each token after attention has updated it with context from other positions."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Formula"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In the original transformer (Vaswani et al. 2017), the FFN uses ReLU activation:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{FFN}(x) = \\max(0,\\; xW_1 + b_1)\\,W_2 + b_2"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "where "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "x"}, {"type": "text", "text": " is a single token's d_model-dimensional representation, W₁ ∈ ℝ^(d_model × d_ff), and W₂ ∈ ℝ^(d_ff × d_model). The intermediate dimension d_ff is typically 4 × d_model, producing a bottleneck that expands and then contracts the representation."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Feed-forward sublayer architecture: input d_model=512 → W1 → hidden d_ff=2048 with GELU activation → W2 → output d_model=512, with activation variants (ReLU, GELU, SwiGLU) and parameter count table"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Implementation"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nclass FeedForwardNetwork(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, d_ff: int, dropout: float = 0.1,\n                 activation: str = 'gelu'):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.W1 = nn.Linear(d_model, d_ff)\n        self.W2 = nn.Linear(d_ff, d_model)\n        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(dropout)\n        if activation == 'relu':\n            self.act = F.relu\n        elif activation == 'gelu':\n            self.act = F.gelu\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(f'Unknown activation: {activation}')\n\n    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:\n        # x: (batch, seq_len, d_model)\n        hidden = self.act(self.W1(x))          # (batch, seq_len, d_ff)\n        hidden = self.dropout(hidden)\n        return self.W2(hidden)                 # (batch, seq_len, d_model)\n\n\n# d_model=512, d_ff=2048 (4× expansion)\nffn = FeedForwardNetwork(d_model=512, d_ff=2048)\nx = torch.randn(2, 16, 512)   # batch=2, seq_len=16\nout = ffn(x)\nprint(out.shape)  # torch.Size([2, 16, 512])\n\n# Parameter count\nn_params = sum(p.numel() for p in ffn.parameters())\nprint(f'{n_params:,}')  # 2,099,712  (≈ 2.1M per FFN layer)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why 4× Expansion?"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Vaswani et al. chose d_ff = 4 × d_model (512 → 2048 in the base model) as an empirical default. The rationale is a trade-off:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Capacity:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " A wider hidden layer gives the FFN more neurons to represent diverse features. The universal approximation perspective suggests more hidden units enable richer functions."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Parameter balance:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " With 4× expansion, each FFN layer uses roughly twice as many parameters as the attention sublayer. In a 12-layer BERT-base: 12 FFN layers × 2.1M ≈ 25M of the 110M total parameters live in FFN layers."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Compute efficiency:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Matrix multiplications at 4× are efficient on modern accelerators. The expansion factor appears in nearly all transformer descendants (GPT, BERT, T5), though modern LLMs like LLaMA use ≈ 8/3 × d_model with SwiGLU."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Activation Functions"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The choice of activation inside the FFN has evolved:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Activation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Formula"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Used in"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Notes"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "ReLU"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "max(0, x)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Original Transformer, T5"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Sparse; many zeros in hidden layer"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GELU"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "x·Φ(x)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BERT, GPT-2/3, RoBERTa"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Smooth; better empirical performance"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "SwiGLU"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "SiLU(xW₁) ⊙ xW₃"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "LLaMA, PaLM, Gemma"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gated; adds a third weight matrix W₃"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "SwiGLU: The Modern Default"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "SwiGLU (Shazeer 2020) uses a gated linear unit: one branch applies the SiLU (also called Swish) activation while a second branch is linear. Their element-wise product controls which neurons are active:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{FFN}_{\\text{SwiGLU}}(x) = \\bigl(\\text{SiLU}(x W_1) \\odot x W_3\\bigr)\\, W_2"}}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nclass SwiGLUFFN(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"SwiGLU feed-forward as used in LLaMA.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, d_ff: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        # d_ff is typically 8/3 * d_model, rounded to a multiple of 256\n        self.W1 = nn.Linear(d_model, d_ff, bias=False)   # gate projection\n        self.W3 = nn.Linear(d_model, d_ff, bias=False)   # up projection\n        self.W2 = nn.Linear(d_ff, d_model, bias=False)   # down projection\n\n    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:\n        # SiLU(x @ W1) * (x @ W3) — gated activation\n        gate = F.silu(self.W1(x))\n        up   = self.W3(x)\n        return self.W2(gate * up)\n\n\n# LLaMA-2 7B: d_model=4096, d_ff=11008 (≈ 8/3 × 4096)\nffn = SwiGLUFFN(d_model=4096, d_ff=11008)\nx = torch.randn(1, 32, 4096)\nout = ffn(x)\nprint(out.shape)  # torch.Size([1, 32, 4096])\nparams = sum(p.numel() for p in ffn.parameters())\nprint(f'{params/1e6:.1f}M params per FFN layer')  # ≈ 135.3M for LLaMA-2 7B layer"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why the FFN Is Needed at All"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Multi-head attention is a linear operation on the value vectors (the softmax weights are fixed given Q and K). Without the FFN, stacking attention layers cannot express more than a linear function. The FFN introduces the "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "non-linearity"}, {"type": "text", "text": " required for the network to approximate arbitrary functions."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Geva et al. (2021) showed that FFN layers act as "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "key-value memories"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": each row of W₁ is a \"key\" that activates when the input matches a pattern, and the corresponding row of W₂ is the \"value\" — a direction in residual-stream space that is added to the output. Language facts (\"Paris is the capital of France\") appear to be stored in specific FFN neurons of specific layers."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Position-Wise: What It Means"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "\"Position-wise\" means the FFN operates on one token at a time, with no interaction between positions. The batch and sequence dimensions are treated as independent examples:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nd_model, d_ff = 4, 8\nW1 = nn.Linear(d_model, d_ff, bias=False)\nW2 = nn.Linear(d_ff, d_model, bias=False)\n\n# Sequence of 3 tokens\nx = torch.randn(3, d_model)   # (seq_len, d_model)\n\n# Applying FFN to the full sequence:\nout_seq = W2(F.gelu(W1(x)))   # (3, d_model)\n\n# Applying FFN token-by-token produces the same result:\nout_tokens = torch.stack([W2(F.gelu(W1(x[i]))) for i in range(3)])\n\nprint(torch.allclose(out_seq, out_tokens, atol=1e-6))  # True\n# The computation is truly position-independent."}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key insight:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " In a transformer block, attention collects information from across the sequence, and the FFN then processes each position's enriched representation independently. This division of labour — cross-position mixing in attention, per-position transformation in FFN — is what makes transformers deep networks rather than shallow linear models. In large models, FFN layers hold the majority of parameters and are believed to store factual knowledge that attention retrieves."}]}]}]}}